problem_solution_en:
【Core Idea】From the optical path equality (Fermat's principle), the intersection curve equation is $n\sqrt{(x-q)^2 + y^2} + n'\sqrt{(x-q')^2 + y^2} = n'q' - nq$, which becomes a quartic equation after rationalization. Three cases for it to become a conic section:
1) $n^2 - n'^2 = 0$ (i.e., $n + n' = 0$, mirror case): the equation reduces to an ellipse or hyperbola;
2) $q = \infty$ ($P$ at infinity): an ellipse if $n' > n$, a hyperbola if $n' < n$;
3) $qn = q'n'$: the equation degenerates to a circle, corresponding to a spherical surface (aplanatic points).
